```class Solution {
public:
    int minimumOneBitOperations(int n) {
        int count = 0;
        while (n != 0) {
            n &= n - 1;
            count++;
        }
        return count;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log(n))
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The problem requires finding the minimum number of operations to set the rightmost bit of the number to 0. We can use a single bitwise AND operation to clear the rightmost bit and increment a counter for each iteration. Since we need to clear the rightmost bit, we can use the bitwise AND operation with a number that has all bits set except the rightmost one. In this case, we use n - 1 to achieve that. The time complexity is O(log(n)) because we iterate until the number becomes 0. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a single counter. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs bitwise operations and does not involve any complex calculations.

